From: SeongJae Park <sj@kernel.org>
Date: Tue, 10 Feb 2026 21:45:16 -0800
Subject: [PATCH] ==== reclaim,lru_sort: monitor all system rams ====

mm/damon/reclaim,lru_sort: monitor all system rams by default

DAMON_RECLAIM and DAMON_LRU_SORT set the biggest 'System RAM' resource
of the system as the default monitoring target address range.  The main
intention behind the design is to minimize the overhead coming from
monitoring of non-System RAM areas.

This could result in an odd setup when there are multiple discrete
System RAMs of considerable sizes.  For example, there are 500 GiB of
System RAM, 500 GiB of System RAM, and 10 MiB of non-System RAM between
those, only the first 500 GiB will be set as the monitoring region by
default.  This is particularly common on NUMA systems.  Hence the
modules allow users to set the monitoring target address range using the
module prameters if the default setup doesn't work for them.  In other
words, the current design trades ease of setup for lower overhead.

However, because DAMON utilizes the sampling based access check and the
adaptive regions adjustment mechanisms, the overhead from the monitoring
of non-System RAM areas should be negligible in most setups.  Meanwhile,
the setup complexity is causing real headaches for users who need to run
those modules on various types of systems.  That is, the current
tradeoff is not a good deal.

Set the phyiscal address range that can cover all System RAM areas of
the system as the default monitoring regions for DAMON_RECLAIM and
DAMON_LRU_SORT.

Technically speaking, this is changing a documented behavior.  However,
it makes no sense to believe there is a real use case that really depend
on the old weird default behavior.  If the old default behavior was
working for them in the reasonable way, this change will only add
negligible amount of monitoring overhead.  If it didn't work, the users
may alredy using manual monitoring regions setup, and they will not be
affected by this change.

Signed-off-by: SeongJae Park <sj@kernel.org>
